    \"metadata\": {
      \"difficulty\": \"medium\",
      \"section_type\": \"situational_judgement\"
    }
  },
  {
    \"type\": \"situational_judgement\",
    \"topic\": \"Ethics & Patient Autonomy\",
    \"stem\": \"An elderly patient with capacity, who has a treatable condition, is refusing a life-saving procedure. Their family is very distressed and insists that you convince the patient to accept treatment, stating the patient 'doesn't know what's best for them'.\",
    \"passage\": null,
    \"options\": [
      \"Explain to the family that the patient has the right to refuse treatment if they have capacity, and ensure the patient understands the consequences of their decision.\",
      \"Attempt to persuade the patient to accept the treatment, emphasizing the family's wishes and the benefits of the procedure.\",
      \"Arrange a meeting with the family and patient to try and reach a compromise on treatment options.\",
      \"Administer the treatment against the patient's will, as it is life-saving and supported by the family.\"
    ],
    \"correct_answer\": 0,
    \"explanation\": \"Respecting patient autonomy is paramount. If a patient has capacity, they have the right to refuse treatment, even if it is life-saving. Your role is to ensure they understand the risks and benefits, and then respect their decision, while also communicating this clearly and empathetically to the family. Administering treatment against their will is unethical and illegal. Persuading them against their clear wishes undermines autonomy.\",
    \"metadata\": {
      \"difficulty\": \"medium\",
      \"section_type\": \"situational_judgement\"
    }
  },
  {
    \"type\": \"situational_judgement\",
    \"topic\": \"Integrity & Honesty\",
    \"stem\": \"You are assisting in a minor procedure. The supervising doctor makes a small error in documenting the procedure in the patient's notes, omitting a minor but relevant detail. They ask you not to mention it, stating it's 'not a big deal'.\",
    \"passage\": null,
    \"options\": [
      \"Agree with the doctor, as it is a minor detail and you don't want to cause trouble.\",
      \"Privately remind the doctor of the importance of accurate documentation and suggest they amend the notes.\",
      \"Amend the notes yourself discreetly without informing the doctor.\",
      \"Report the doctor's omission to a more senior colleague immediately.\"
    ],
    \"correct_answer\": 1,
    \"explanation\": \"Accurate documentation is crucial for patient safety and professional integrity. The most appropriate first step is to politely and privately remind the supervising doctor of the importance of accuracy and suggest they correct the omission. This maintains professionalism while upholding ethical standards. Amending notes yourself is inappropriate, and immediate formal reporting might be an overreaction for a minor omission that can be easily corrected.\",
    \"metadata\": {
      \"difficulty\": \"medium\",
      \"section_type\": \"situational_judgement\"
    }
  },
  {
    \"type\": \"situational_judgement\",
    \"topic\": \"Accountability & Learning from Mistakes\",
    \"stem\": \"As a junior doctor, you accidentally administer a slightly incorrect dose of a non-critical medication to a stable patient. The patient shows no adverse effects. You immediately realise your mistake.\",
    \"passage\": null,
    \"options\": [
      \"Monitor the patient closely and say nothing, as no harm was done.\",
      \"Immediately inform your supervising doctor and document the error in the patient's notes.\",
      \"Inform the patient about the error and apologise profusely.\",
      \"Inform a colleague and ask them to help you cover it up.\"
    ],
    \"correct_answer\": 1,
    \"explanation\": \"Patient safety and professional accountability require immediate action. You must inform your supervising doctor and document the error, even if no harm occurred. This allows for proper monitoring, assessment, and learning from the mistake. Covering it up is unprofessional and dangerous. Informing the patient before your supervisor might cause unnecessary alarm, and your supervisor needs to be aware to guide further action.\",
    \"metadata\": {
      \"difficulty\": \"medium\",
      \"section_type\": \"situational_judgement\"
