  {
    \"type\": \"situational_judgement\",
    \"topic\": \"Confidentiality & Minors\",
    \"stem\": \"A 15-year-old patient confides in you about a sensitive health issue and explicitly asks you not to tell their parents. You assess them as having sufficient capacity to understand the implications of their decision.\",
    \"passage\": null,
    \"options\": [
      \"Inform the parents immediately, as they are still a minor.\",
      \"Respect their request for confidentiality, provided you believe they have capacity and are not at significant risk of harm.\",
      \"Tell the patient you cannot keep secrets from their parents and advise them to tell them.\",
      \"Document the issue and their request for confidentiality, then seek advice from a senior colleague on how to proceed.\"
    ],
    \"correct_answer\": 1,
    \"explanation\": \"In many jurisdictions, minors (especially those 16 or older, and sometimes younger if 'Gillick competent' or 'Fraser competent') have a right to confidentiality if they have the capacity to make their own decisions. If you assess them as having capacity and not being at significant risk of harm, their confidentiality should be respected. Seeking advice from a senior colleague (without breaking confidentiality) is a good step if unsure about capacity or risk, but generally, the patient's wishes are paramount if competent.\",
    \"metadata\": {
      \"difficulty\": \"medium\",
      \"section_type\": \"situational_judgement\"
    }
  },
  {
    \"type\": \"situational_judgement\",
    \"topic\": \"Professionalism & Integrity\",
    \"stem\": \"You are asked to write a letter of recommendation for a peer for a competitive program. You know this peer well, and while they are a good person, their academic performance and clinical skills are only average, and you don't feel you can give a strong endorsement.\",
    \"passage\": null,
